### Part 2: ParagraphCommentLayer -- The Paragraph Detection Engine

**New file: `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\Stories\ChapterReader\ParagraphCommentLayer.jsx`**

This is the trickiest component. It must overlay interactive badges on top of Lexical-rendered paragraph elements without breaking the reader's layout or scroll behavior.

**Strategy:**

1. Accept a `containerRef` that points to the `.chapter-reader-body` div
2. After Lexical renders content, use a `MutationObserver` on the container to detect when `.editor-paragraph` elements appear
3. Once detected, query all paragraphs, assign each a `data-paragraph-index` attribute (based on DOM order), and compute a fingerprint (first 100 chars of `textContent`)
4. Store paragraph metadata in state: `[{ index, fingerprint, element }]`
5. Render an absolutely positioned badge for each paragraph that has comments (or on hover for all paragraphs)
6. Use a `ResizeObserver` + scroll listener to reposition badges when layout shifts

**Component structure:**

```jsx
const ParagraphCommentLayer = ({ containerRef, commentCounts, onParagraphClick }) => {
    const [paragraphs, setParagraphs] = useState([]);
    const [badgePositions, setBadgePositions] = useState([]);
    const [hoveredIndex, setHoveredIndex] = useState(null);

    // Step 1: Detect paragraphs after Lexical renders
    useEffect(() => {
        const container = containerRef.current;
        if (!container) return;

        const scanParagraphs = () => {
            const els = container.querySelectorAll('.editor-paragraph');
            const meta = Array.from(els).map((el, i) => {
                el.setAttribute('data-paragraph-index', i);
                return {
                    index: i,
                    fingerprint: el.textContent.substring(0, 100),
                    element: el,
                };
            });
            setParagraphs(meta);
        };

        // MutationObserver catches Lexical's initial render
        const observer = new MutationObserver(() => {
            scanParagraphs();
        });
        observer.observe(container, { childList: true, subtree: true });

        // Initial scan in case content already rendered
        scanParagraphs();

        return () => observer.disconnect();
    }, [containerRef]);

    // Step 2: Position badges relative to container
    useEffect(() => {
        if (paragraphs.length === 0) return;

        const updatePositions = () => {
            const containerRect = containerRef.current?.getBoundingClientRect();
            if (!containerRect) return;

            const positions = paragraphs.map(p => {
                const rect = p.element.getBoundingClientRect();
                return {
                    index: p.index,
                    top: rect.top - containerRect.top,
                    height: rect.height,
                };
            });
            setBadgePositions(positions);
        };

        updatePositions();

        // ResizeObserver for layout changes
        const resizeObs = new ResizeObserver(updatePositions);
        if (containerRef.current) resizeObs.observe(containerRef.current);

        // Scroll listener for repositioning
        window.addEventListener('scroll', updatePositions, { passive: true });

        return () => {
            resizeObs.disconnect();
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', updatePositions);
        };
    }, [paragraphs, containerRef]);

    // Step 3: Hover detection on paragraph elements
    useEffect(() => {
        const handlers = paragraphs.map(p => {
            const enter = () => setHoveredIndex(p.index);
            const leave = () => setHoveredIndex(null);
            p.element.addEventListener('mouseenter', enter);
            p.element.addEventListener('mouseleave', leave);
            return { element: p.element, enter, leave };
        });

        return () => {
            handlers.forEach(h => {
                h.element.removeEventListener('mouseenter', h.enter);
                h.element.removeEventListener('mouseleave', h.leave);
            });
        };
    }, [paragraphs]);

    return (
        <div className="pcl-badge-layer">
            {badgePositions.map(pos => {
                const count = commentCounts?.[String(pos.index)] || 0;
                const isHovered = hoveredIndex === pos.index;
                const show = count > 0 || isHovered;

                if (!show) return null;

                return (
                    <motion.button
                        key={pos.index}
                        className={`pcl-badge ${count > 0 ? 'pcl-badge-active' : ''}`}
                        style={{ top: pos.top + pos.height / 2 - 12 }}
                        onClick={() => onParagraphClick(pos.index, paragraphs[pos.index]?.fingerprint)}
                        initial={{ opacity: 0, scale: 0.8 }}
                        animate={{ opacity: 1, scale: 1 }}
                        exit={{ opacity: 0, scale: 0.8 }}
                        transition={{ duration: 0.15 }}
                        title={count > 0 ? `${count} comment${count !== 1 ? 's' : ''}` : 'Add a comment'}
                    >
                        {/* Comment bubble SVG icon */}
                        <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2">
                            <path d="M21 15a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h14a2 2 0 0 1 2 2z" />
                        </svg>
                        {count > 0 && <span className="pcl-badge-count">{count}</span>}
                    </motion.button>
                );
            })}
        </div>
    );
};
```

**Key design decisions:**

- The badge layer is a sibling to the Lexical content, positioned absolutely within the `.chapter-reader-body` wrapper (which gets `position: relative`)
- Badges appear in the right margin, offset from the container's right edge
- On mobile (under 768px), badges are smaller and appear as a thin margin indicator instead of a full badge, to avoid crowding the reading experience
- The `MutationObserver` approach is necessary because Lexical renders asynchronously after `editor.setEditorState()` is called. A simple `useEffect` after the hook data arrives would miss the actual DOM rendering
- Paragraph fingerprinting uses `textContent.substring(0, 100)` which matches the backend's `paragraph_fingerprint` column. This allows comments to be re-anchored if paragraphs are reordered in future edits

